5|$|In {{the sixth}} century, Caesarius of Arles taught {{that the whole}} glory of the Jewish <b>Sabbath</b> had been {{transferred}} to Sunday and that Christians must keep Sunday {{in the same way}} as the Jews were commanded to keep the <b>Sabbath.</b> The Council of Orléans in 538 reprobated this tendency, to apply the law of the Jewish <b>Sabbath</b> to the observance of the Christian Sunday, as Jewish and non-Christian.|$|E
5|$|Shabbat {{lunch is}} also an {{important}} social meal. Since antiquity, Jewish communities all over the world devised meat casseroles that begin cooking before the lighting of candles that marks the commencement of the <b>Sabbath</b> on Friday night, so as to comply with the religious regulations for observing the <b>Sabbath.</b> In modern Israel, this filling dish, in many variations, is still eaten on the <b>Sabbath</b> day, not only in religiously observant households, and is also served in some restaurants during the week.|$|E
5|$|The English {{heavy metal}} band Black <b>Sabbath</b> {{appropriated}} their {{name from the}} film. Originally known as Earth, the group wanted to change their name as another group had the same name. The group saw a local cinema playing Black <b>Sabbath</b> and marveled that people paid money to be frightened.|$|E
